In 1994, Prince Charles admitted to infidelity after his marriage to Princess Diana had broken down.
Despite opposition from some Anglicans, Charles and Camilla will marry in a civil ceremony at Windsor Castle.
Prime Minister Tony Blair expressed his happiness for the couple.
The Archbishop of Canterbury welcomed the news, hoping it brings comfort.
Charles's sons, William and Harry, are delighted.
Camilla will be known as the Duchess of Cornwall, not the queen.
The public's reaction is mixed, with some still holding Princess Diana in high regard.
The enduring love story of Charles and Camilla is seen as a poignant contrast to disposable relationships.
